      <!-- Maintenance -->
      <div class="card" id="maintenance">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Which material needs the least maintenance?</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p><strong>Face brick — by a clear margin.</strong> No repainting, just occasional cleaning. Render and cladding both need repainting every few years, and cladding can require caulking refreshes as panels expand and contract. The choice of material drives the rest of the lifetime maintenance picture below.</p>

          <div class="table-scroll">
            <table class="data-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Material</th>
                  <th>Pros</th>
                  <th>Cons</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Bricks</strong></td>
                  <td>✅ No repainting and minimal maintenance to retain the look.</td>
                  <td>
                    ❌ Parapet walls without cappings commonly discolour — water doesn't drain away and streaks form.<br>
                    ❌ If the colour is painted on (entry-level bricks), chips will expose the reddish base colour underneath.
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Render</strong></td>
                  <td>✅ A good paint can retain the colour for a long time. Acrylic render helps reduce cracking.</td>
                  <td>
                    ❌ Needs repainting every few years as paint discolours or stains.<br>
                    ❌ Cracks need patching.<br>
                    ❌ Patching can be costly — EPS is easier and cheaper to patch than Hebel.
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Cladding</strong></td>
                  <td>✅ Some cladding systems let you replace broken panels easily.</td>
                  <td>
                    ❌ Needs repainting every few years as paint discolours or stains.<br>
                    ❌ Thermal expansion can open gaps — caulking may need refreshing in some areas.
                  </td>
                </tr>
